2026-05-17 19:25:25 | DEBUG | strands_evaluation.instrumentation.agent_plugins | Model response #7 [role=assistant block=1 tool_use] execute_code({"code": "import pandas as pd\nimport math\n\n# load files using DOWNLOAD_PATHS\nrc_path = DOWNLOAD_PATHS['s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-easy-8/files/roman_cities.csv']\nwc_path = DOWNLOAD_PATHS['s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-hard-12/files/worldcities.csv']\n\nrc = pd.read_csv(rc_path)\nwc = pd.read_csv(wc_path)\n\nprint('roman rows, worldcity rows:', len(rc), len(wc))\n\n# inspect column names\nprint('roman columns:', rc.columns.tolist())\nprint('world columns:', wc.columns.tolist())\n\n# rename roman lon/lat to numeric\nrc = rc.rename(columns={rc.columns[9]:'lon', rc.columns[10]:'lat'})\nrc['lon'] = pd.to_numeric(rc['lon'], errors='coerce')\nrc['lat'] = pd.to_numeric(rc['lat'], errors='coerce')\nrc = rc.dropna(subset=['lon','lat'])\n\n# world cities: lat/lng, population\nwc['lat'] = pd.to_numeric(wc['lat'], errors='coerce')\nwc['lng'] = pd.to_numeric(wc['lng'], errors='coerce')\nwc['population'] = pd.to_numeric(wc['population'], errors='coerce')\nwc = wc.dropna(subset=['lat','lng','population'])\n\n# filter modern cities population>100000\nwc_large = wc[wc['population']>100000].copy()\nprint('world cities >100k:', len(wc_large))\n\n# compute angular distance in degrees: use great-circle central angle in degrees\n# formula: central_angle = arccos(sin φ1 sin φ2 + cos φ1 cos φ2 cos(Δλ)) in radians then degrees\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef central_angle_deg(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):\n    # lat/lon in degrees\n    phi1 = np.deg2rad(lat1)\n    phi2 = np.deg2rad(lat2)\n    dl = np.deg2rad(lon2 - lon1)\n    cos_ang = np.sin(phi1)*np.sin(phi2) + np.cos(phi1)*np.cos(phi2)*np.cos(dl)\n    # numeric issues\n    cos_ang = np.minimum(1, np.maximum(-1, cos_ang))\n    ang = np.arccos(cos_ang)\n    return np.rad2deg(ang)\n\n# For efficiency, we'll loop over roman cities and mark matching modern city ids\nmodern_match_ids = set()\n\n# Convert modern city positions to arrays\nmod_lats = wc_large['lat'].values\nmod_lons = wc_large['lng'].values\nmod_ids = wc_large['id'].values\n\n# iterate roman cities\nfor idx, row in rc.iterrows():\n    rlat = row['lat']\n    rlon = row['lon']\n    # compute central angle to all modern cities vectorized\n    angs = central_angle_deg(rlat, rlon, mod_lats, mod_lons)\n    within = angs <= 0.1\n    if within.any():\n        ids = mod_ids[within]\n        for mid in ids:\n            modern_match_ids.add(int(mid))\n\nprint('unique modern cities within 0.1 deg of any roman city:', len(modern_match_ids))\nprint('sample matched city count and few ids:', len(modern_match_ids), list(sorted(list(modern_match_ids)))[:10])\n\n# Also output matched city names for sanity\nmatched = wc_large[wc_large['id'].isin(modern_match_ids)][['city','city_ascii','lat','lng','population','id']]\nprint(matched.head(10).to_csv(index=False))\n\n# final print for tool\nprint(len(modern_match_ids))\n"}) [toolUseId=call_WzEVRP8EzxbXW2f5KM0rEOQi]
2026-05-17 19:25:25 | INFO | strands_evaluation.instrumentation.agent_plugins | Executing: execute_code({"code": "import pandas as pd\nimport math\n\n# load files using DOWNLOAD_PATHS\nrc_path = DOWNLOAD_PATHS['s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-easy-8/files/roman_cities.csv']\nwc_path = DOWNLOAD_PATHS['s3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-hard-12/files/worldcities.csv']\n\nrc = pd.read_csv(rc_path)\nwc = pd.read_csv(wc_path)\n\nprint('roman rows, worldcity rows:', len(rc), len(wc))\n\n# inspect column names\nprint('roman columns:', rc.columns.tolist())\nprint('world columns:', wc.columns.tolist())\n\n# rename roman lon/lat to numeric\nrc = rc.rename(columns={rc.columns[9]:'lon', rc.columns[10]:'lat'})\nrc['lon'] = pd.to_numeric(rc['lon'], errors='coerce')\nrc['lat'] = pd.to_numeric(rc['lat'], errors='coerce')\nrc = rc.dropna(subset=['lon','lat'])\n\n# world cities: lat/lng, population\nwc['lat'] = pd.to_numeric(wc['lat'], errors='coerce')\nwc['lng'] = pd.to_numeric(wc['lng'], errors='coerce')\nwc['population'] = pd.to_numeric(wc['population'], errors='coerce')\nwc = wc.dropna(subset=['lat','lng','population'])\n\n# filter modern cities population>100000\nwc_large = wc[wc['population']>100000].copy()\nprint('world cities >100k:', len(wc_large))\n\n# compute angular distance in degrees: use great-circle central angle in degrees\n# formula: central_angle = arccos(sin φ1 sin φ2 + cos φ1 cos φ2 cos(Δλ)) in radians then degrees\nimport numpy as np\n\ndef central_angle_deg(lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):\n    # lat/lon in degrees\n    phi1 = np.deg2rad(lat1)\n    phi2 = np.deg2rad(lat2)\n    dl = np.deg2rad(lon2 - lon1)\n    cos_ang = np.sin(phi1)*np.sin(phi2) + np.cos(phi1)*np.cos(phi2)*np.cos(dl)\n    # numeric issues\n    cos_ang = np.minimum(1, np.maximum(-1, cos_ang))\n    ang = np.arccos(cos_ang)\n    return np.rad2deg(ang)\n\n# For efficiency, we'll loop over roman cities and mark matching modern city ids\nmodern_match_ids = set()\n\n# Convert modern city positions to arrays\nmod_lats = wc_large['lat'].values\nmod_lons = wc_large['lng'].values\nmod_ids = wc_large['id'].values\n\n# iterate roman cities\nfor idx, row in rc.iterrows():\n    rlat = row['lat']\n    rlon = row['lon']\n    # compute central angle to all modern cities vectorized\n    angs = central_angle_deg(rlat, rlon, mod_lats, mod_lons)\n    within = angs <= 0.1\n    if within.any():\n        ids = mod_ids[within]\n        for mid in ids:\n            modern_match_ids.add(int(mid))\n\nprint('unique modern cities within 0.1 deg of any roman city:', len(modern_match_ids))\nprint('sample matched city count and few ids:', len(modern_match_ids), list(sorted(list(modern_match_ids)))[:10])\n\n# Also output matched city names for sanity\nmatched = wc_large[wc_large['id'].isin(modern_match_ids)][['city','city_ascii','lat','lng','population','id']]\nprint(matched.head(10).to_csv(index=False))\n\n# final print for tool\nprint(len(modern_match_ids))\n"})
